<p>The combined oral contraceptive pill COCP, often referred to as the birth control pill or colloquially as the pill, is a type of birth control that is designed to be taken orally by women. They are used by more than million women worldwide 12 13 including about 9 million women in the United States. Combined oral contraceptive pills were developed to prevent ovulation by suppressing the release of gonadotropins. Combined hormonal contraceptives, including COCPs, inhibit follicular development and prevent ovulation as a primary mechanism of action. Under normal circumstances, luteinizing hormone LH stimulates the theca cells of the ovarian follicle to produce androstenedione. The granulosa cells of the ovarian follicle then convert this androstenedione to estradiol. Decreased levels of FSH inhibit follicular development, preventing an increase in estradiol levels. Inhibition of follicular development and the absence of an LH surge prevent ovulation. Estrogen was originally included in oral contraceptives for better cycle control to stabilize the endometrium and thereby reduce the incidence of breakthrough bleeding, but was also found to inhibit follicular development and help prevent ovulation.</p>


